In this section we consider conformal equivalence of domains $D \subset \mathbb{R}^{2}$ equipped with differential $1$-forms $\theta \in \Omega^{1}(D)$.
As above this problem can be reformulated as equivalence problem for differential $1$-forms defined on the
unit  disk $\mathbb{D}$ with respect to the group of M\"{o}bius transformations.

We denote by $\tau^{\ast}: T^{\ast}\mathbb{D} \rightarrow \mathbb{D}$ the cotangent bundle with canonical coordinates $(x, y, u, v)$ and by $J^{k}(\tau^{\ast})$ the bundles of $k$-jets of sections of $\tau^{\ast}$ with standard canonical coordinates $(x, y, u, v, u_{10}, u_{01}, v_{10}, v_{11}, u_{11}, \ldots)$.
Any differential $1$-form $\theta \in \Omega^{1}(\mathbb{D})$,
$
\theta = a(x,y)dx+b(x,y)dy
$
could be viewed as a section $S_{\theta}$ of the cotangent bundle, where
$$
S_{\theta} : (x,y) \longmapsto (u=a(x,y), v=b(x,y)).
$$
The universal Liouville  $1$-form $\omega \in \Omega^{1}T^{\ast}\mathbb{D}$$
\omega=udx+vdy
$
equalizes these two points of view:
$
\theta=S_{\theta}^{\ast}(\omega).
$
The $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-action on the unit disk $\mathbb{D}$ has the natural lift to $T^{\ast}\mathbb{D}$ and the correspondent Lie algebra $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-representation by vector fields is given by the following Hamiltonian vector fields:
$$
%\begin{array}{ll}
\overline{X}=X+u\partial_{v}-v\partial_{u}, \quad
\overline{Y}=Y-2(xu+yv)\partial_{u}-2(xv-yu)\partial_{v}, \quad
\overline{Z}=z+2(xv-yu)\partial_{u}-2(xu+yv)\partial_{v}.
%\end{array}
$$
Using the complex structure $I$ and the Liouville form $\omega$ we get coframe on $T^{\ast}\mathbb{D}$:
\begin{equation}
\label{22}
%\begin{array}{ll}
\omega_{1}=\omega=udx+vdy,\quad
\omega_{2}=I\omega=-vdx+udy,
%\end{array}
\end{equation}
which is obviously invariant with respect to conformal transformations.

The structure equations for this coframe:
$$
\widehat{d}\omega_{1}=\frac{v_{10}-u_{01}}{u^{2}+v^{2}} \omega_{1} \wedge \omega_{2},
\quad
\widehat{d}\omega_{2}=\frac{u_{10}+v_{01}}{u^{2}+v^{2}} \omega_{1} \wedge \omega_{2},
$$
give us two $1$-st order conformal differential invariants
$$
J_{11}=\frac{v_{10}-u_{01}}{u^{2}+v^{2}},
\quad
J_{12}=\frac{u_{10}+v_{01}}{u^{2}+v^{2}}.
$$
In addition to them we have also obvious metric differential invariant of order zero:
$
J_{0}=g(\omega, \omega)=t^{2}(u^{2}+v^{2}).
$
We say that a point (or $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-orbit) in $J^{k}(\tau^{\ast})$ is \textit{regular} if $J_{0} \neq 0$ at this point.

The frame dual to coframe $\langle \omega_{1}, \omega_{2} \rangle$ in the domain of regular points consist of two conformally invariant total derivations:
$$
\delta_{1}=\frac{1}{u^{2}+v^{2}}\bigg( u\frac{d}{dx}+v\frac{d}{dy} \bigg),
\quad
\delta_{2}=\frac{1}{u^{2}+v^{2}}\bigg( -v\frac{d}{dx}+u\frac{d}{dy} \bigg).
$$
Remark that invariant $J_{0}$ separates regular orbits in $J^{0}(\tau^{\ast})$ and therefore generates the field of rational differential $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-invariants of order zero.
Moreover, the $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-action in $J^{k}(\tau^{\ast})$, when $k \geq 1$, is free at regular points.
Therefore, counting of codimensions of regular orbits, we arrive at the following description of the field of rational differential $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-invariants.
\begin{theorem}
The field of rational differential $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-invariants of differential $1$-forms is generated by differential invariants $J_{0}$, $J_{11}$, $J_{12}$ of order $\leq 1$ and invariant derivations $\delta_{1}$, $\delta_{2}$.
\end{theorem}
For low level jets we have the following generators in the fields of differential invariants:
$$
%\begin{array}{ll}
%\qquad 
k=0, \quad J_{0}; \qquad k=1, \quad J_{0}, J_{11}, J_{12}, \delta_{1}(J_{0}), \delta_{2}(J_{0}); 
$$$$
k=2, \quad J_{0}, J_{11}, J_{12}, \delta_{1}(J_{0}), \delta_{2}(J_{0}), \delta_{1}(J_{11}), 
 \delta_{1}(J_{12}), \delta_{2}(J_{11}), \delta_{2}(J_{12}), \delta_{i}\delta_{j}(J_{0}).
%\end{array}
$$
Remark that codimention of regular orbits in $J^{2}(\tau^{\ast})$ is equal to $11$ but in our description we have $12$ generators. If means that we have one differential syzygy in order two.
Straightforward computations show that this syzygy has the form:
\begin{equation}
\label{3}
\begin{array}{ll}
2J_{0}^{2} \bigg( J_{11}^{2}+J_{12}^{2}+\delta_{2}(J_{11}^{2})+\delta_{1}(J_{12}^{2}) \bigg)- \\
-J_{0} \bigg( J_{12}\delta_{1}(J_{0})-J_{11}\delta_{2}(J_{0})-\delta_{1}^{2}(J_{0})-\delta_{2}^{2}(J_{0}) \bigg)+ \delta_{1}(J_{0})^{2}+\delta_{2}(J_{0})^{2}-8J_{0}=0.
\end{array}
\end{equation}
Let $\theta \in \Omega^{1}(\mathbb{D})$ be a differential $1$-form.
We say that $\theta$ is \textit{regular} if $J_{0}(\theta) \neq 0$ and values of some two differential invariants,
say $A$ and $B$, of order $\leq 1$ on $\theta$ are independent.
Then, to know the restriction of the differential invariant field on the form $\Theta$, we have to know values:
\begin{equation}
\label{4}
%\left \{
%\begin{array}{rcl}
J_{0}(\theta)=F(A,B); \quad J_{11}(\theta)=G(A,B); \quad J_{12}(\theta)=H(A,B),
%\end{array}
%\right.
\end{equation}
as well as
\begin{equation}
\label{5}
%\bigg \{
%\begin{array}{cc}
\delta_{1}(A)(\theta)=A_{1}(A,B), \quad \delta_{1}(B)(\theta)=B_{1}(A,B),
%\end{array}
%\end{equation}
%\begin{equation}
%\label{6}
%\bigg \{
%\begin{array}{cc}
\delta_{2}(A)(\theta)=A_{2}(A,B), \quad
\delta_{2}(B)(\theta)=B_{2}(A,B).
%\end{array}
\end{equation}
Remark that equations (\ref{4}), (\ref{5}) allow us to find values of all differential invariants of order $2$ on $\theta$.
Therefore, (\ref{4}), (\ref{5}) is a Frobenius type system  differential equations which is completely integrable and  $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-invariant.
The dimension of the solutions space is equal three and each solution completely defined by its $1$-jet at a point.
Summarizing, we get the following $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-classification of regular differential $1$-forms on the disk.
\begin{theorem}
A $PSL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$-orbit of a regular differential $1$-form on the unit disk is defined by functions
$F$, $G$, $H$, $A_{1}$, $A_{2}$, $B_{1}$, $B_{2}$ subjected to zyzygy relation
(\ref{3}).
\end{theorem}
